## Critical reminders (safeguard when rule not in context)

These bullets are the single source of truth: the sessionStart hook (`.cursor/hooks/AIC-session-init.cjs`) reads this section and injects them at session start. Keep each bullet concise and one-line so the hook output stays compact.

- **aic_compile (MANDATORY):** Your FIRST action on EVERY message — including follow-ups — is to call the `aic_compile` MCP tool with `{ "intent": "<search query: name the files, components, interfaces, or actions involved>", "projectRoot": "/Users/jatbas/Desktop/AIC", "conversationId": "<from AIC_CONVERSATION_ID in system prompt, if available>" }`. The intent drives file selection — write it like a search query with domain terms, not a prose summary. Good: `"fix IntentClassifier token extraction in pipeline storage intent-quality"`. Bad: `"user wants to fix a bug"`. If `AIC_CONVERSATION_ID=<uuid>` appears in your system prompt (injected at session start), include that value as `conversationId` in every aic_compile call. Never skip because you "already have context." Each message needs fresh, intent-specific context. The response JSON includes `conversationId` (string or null) — store this value and use it when calling `aic_chat_summary`.
- **First pass:** Apply these rules when writing code so the first version passes lint and conventions; avoid rework and double token use.
- **SOLID:** One public method per class; one class per file; one interface per `*.interface.ts` file. Constructor receives only interfaces — never concrete classes. No `public` constructor params in pipeline — use `private readonly`. No exported interfaces in pipeline files — extract to `core/interfaces/`. Max 60 lines per function in pipeline (enforced by ESLint). No exceptions in pipeline steps.
- **Hexagonal:** `core/` and `pipeline/` have zero imports from `adapters/`, `storage/`, `mcp/`, Node.js APIs, or external packages. All I/O through interfaces only. Core interfaces must NOT expose infrastructure concepts (SQL syntax, HTTP verbs, file-system paths) — use domain terminology.
- **Adapter wrapping:** Every external library has exactly ONE adapter or storage file that wraps it behind a core interface. No other file imports the library directly — enforced by ESLint `no-restricted-imports`. To swap a library, change one file.
- **DIP:** No `new` for infrastructure/service classes outside the MCP composition boundary: `mcp/src/server.ts` is the primary wiring site; delegated `new` in other `mcp/src` modules follows `aic-mcp.mdc` (Composition Root Discipline). All dependencies via constructor injection. Storage classes receive the database instance — never construct it. Adapters inject `Clock` for time, never call `Date.now()` directly.
- **OCP:** New capabilities via new classes implementing existing interfaces — never modify existing pipeline classes. The core pipeline is frozen once correct; all evolution happens at the edges.
- **Dispatch pattern:** No if/else-if chains with 3+ branches — enforced by ESLint. Use `Record<Enum, Handler>` for enum dispatch, handler arrays for predicate dispatch. Extend by adding entries (OCP), not modifying branches.
- **Errors:** Never throw bare `Error`. Use `AicError` subclasses with machine-readable `code` property. Pipeline steps never catch-and-ignore — errors propagate to composition root. MCP server never crashes on a single bad request.
- **Determinism:** No `Date.now()`, `new Date()`, or `Math.random()` anywhere — enforced by ESLint globally. Only `system-clock.ts` is exempt. All other code injects time via `Clock` interface. No `date('now')` or `datetime('now')` in SQL — pass the current timestamp as a bound parameter from the `Clock` interface.
- **Immutability:** No `.push()`, `.splice()`, `.sort()` (mutating), `.reverse()` (mutating). Use spread/reduce. Pipeline steps never mutate their inputs — return new objects. No `let` in production code — use `const` exclusively. Only exception: boolean control flags in imperative closures (e.g. `let found = false` in a `ts.forEachChild` visitor). Accumulators must use reduce or a helper that returns the collected result — never `let arr = []; ... arr = [...arr, item]`.
- **Types:** No `any`. Explicit return types on all functions. Interfaces in `*.interface.ts` files (one interface per file). Max 5 methods per interface (ISP). Related type aliases live in `core/types/`, not in interface files.
- **Named imports only (enforced by ESLint):** No `import * as X` for internal modules (relative or `#alias` paths). Use named imports: `import { A, B } from "./foo.js"`. Namespace imports allowed only for Node.js built-ins (`import * as path from "node:path"`) and established library APIs (`import * as ts from "typescript"`).
- **Comments:** `//` style only — `/* */` and `/** */` block comments are banned by ESLint. One short line max, explain _why_ not _what_. No JSDoc. No narrating comments (`// Get the user`, `// Return result`).
- **Branded types (ADR-010):** Use `shared/src/core/types/` branded types — never raw `string`/`number` for domain values (paths, tokens, durations, scores, IDs, enums). `as const` objects for enums, not TS `enum`. Null = `Type | null`; optional = `?: Type`.
- **Type safety (enforced by ESLint):** No `as string`, `as number`, `as boolean` — branded types are already their base type. No double-cast `as unknown as T` (only `open-database.ts` exempt). No `!` non-null assertions — use optional chaining or null guards. No `Partial<T>` in core/pipeline. No `{ x } as Type` object literal assertions — use type annotations. No `enum`, `for...in`, default exports, `Object.assign`, nested ternaries. See `.cursor/rules/AIC-type-safety.mdc`.
- **Validation boundary (ADR-009):** Runtime validation at MCP handler and config loader only. Core/pipeline never imports the validation library — trusts branded types.
- **Database:** All SQL lives exclusively in `shared/src/storage/`. Every schema change requires a migration file in `shared/src/storage/migrations/`. Never run raw DDL outside the `MigrationRunner`.
- **Global DB:** The database is a single file at `~/.aic/aic.sqlite`. Per-project isolation is enforced via `project_id` in store queries (all per-project stores take `projectId: ProjectId` and use `WHERE project_id = ?`).
- **IDs:** All entity PKs use UUIDv7 (`TEXT(36)` in SQLite). Never `INTEGER AUTOINCREMENT` for entities. Exception: `config_history` uses composite PK `(project_id, config_hash)` with SHA-256 `config_hash`. See Project Plan ADR-007.
- **Timestamps:** Always `YYYY-MM-DDTHH:mm:ss.sssZ` (UTC, milliseconds, trailing `Z`). Use the `Clock` interface — never `new Date()` or `Date.now()` directly. Use the `ISOTimestamp` branded type. See Project Plan ADR-008.
- **Docs as source of truth:** Read `documentation/` before proposing or changing code. The Project Plan is the architecture spec. The implementation specification (`documentation/implementation-spec.md`) is the implementation contract.
- **Commits:** Format `type(scope): description`, max 72 chars, target 50-60, imperative, no period. Subject line only — no body or footer. Never use `--no-verify`.
- **File ops:** Use targeted edits (search_replace / minimal edit) on the minimum necessary lines. Do not read a file and write a new file when an in-place edit suffices.
- **No .md without instruction:** Do not create or modify any .md file (documentation/, README, .cursor/rules/, etc.) unless the user explicitly asks you to.
- **Read scope:** Read only the file sections you need for this change; avoid full-file reads when not needed (use offset/limit for large files).
- **Secrets:** Never hardcode API keys, tokens, or credentials in source. Config references env var _names_ (`apiKeyEnv: "OPENAI_API_KEY"`), never values. All logging must sanitize secrets — replace with `***`.
- **`.aic/` security:** Directory is `0700` (owner-only), auto-gitignored, no symlink traversal. Storage code must enforce these invariants.
- **Telemetry data:** Telemetry payloads must never contain file paths, file content, prompts, intents, project names, or PII. Only typed aggregates and enum values. See `security.md §Anonymous Telemetry`.
- **Dependencies:** All versions pinned exact (`"9.39.3"`, never `"^9.0.0"`). Adding a runtime dep requires justification. One dep per PR. See Project Plan §16.
- **File naming:** All `.ts` files use kebab-case (`intent-classifier.ts`). Interfaces: `*.interface.ts`. Tests: `*.test.ts`. Migrations: `NNN-description.ts`. Documentation: kebab-case except conventional root files (`README.md`).
- **No rule bypass:** Never add `eslint-disable`, `eslint-disable-next-line`, `@ts-ignore`, or `@ts-nocheck` comments. If a rule fires, fix the code — do not silence the rule. If a rule genuinely does not apply, request a targeted override in `eslint.config.mjs`.
- **Lint:** Prefer `npx eslint` for checks; `read_lints` can be stale. Run `pnpm lint` before declaring work complete. Run `pnpm knip` to check for unused files, exports, and dependencies.
- **Smoke tests:** When editing `integrations/**`, `mcp/scripts/bundle-*`, or `mcp/package.json` `files` field, verify `integrations/__tests__/pack-install-smoke.test.cjs` still passes and update its assertions if you changed the published artifact layout, install behavior, or uninstall behavior. Run: `node integrations/__tests__/pack-install-smoke.test.cjs`.
- **Skill execution mode:** Complex multi-step skills (task-planner, task-executor, researcher, documentation-writer, roadmap-forge) require a full-agent execution mode that preserves instruction fidelity — in Cursor, use Composer (Agent). Auto mode may not reliably follow lengthy structured protocols: it can compress, reorder, or skip phases. Single-step skills (update-changelog, update-progress) work in any mode.
- **Verify before implementing:** For any request — ad-hoc or skill-driven — investigate first: query the actual database, read the actual deployed file, check the actual API response, trace the actual bootstrap code path. Never implement based on assumptions about external system behavior (editor internals, third-party formats, undocumented APIs, runtime payloads). If the assumption cannot be verified with real data, tell the user before writing code. This rule applies to ALL skills (planner, executor, researcher) — each skill has its own reinforcement: planner §0b Runtime Verification Checklist, executor §2.5 Verify External Assumptions, researcher §3a Runtime Evidence Mandate. Regardless of execution mode, the skill's verification steps are the enforcement mechanism.
- **Evidence before claims:** Never claim work is complete, tests pass, or a bug is fixed without fresh verification evidence from the current message. Run the command, read the output, THEN make the claim. Words like "should", "probably", or "seems to" indicate missing evidence — run the verification instead. This applies to all completion claims: test results, lint results, build results, bug fixes, requirements met, and subagent success reports. Trust tool output, not memory.
- **Systematic debugging:** When encountering any bug, test failure, or unexpected behavior, follow the systematic debugging process: (1) investigate root cause before proposing fixes, (2) reproduce consistently, (3) form and test single hypotheses, (4) create a failing test before fixing. If 3+ fix attempts fail, stop and question the architecture — the pattern may be wrong, not the code. Use the `aic-systematic-debugging` skill for the full process.
- **File size awareness:** You reason best about code you can hold in context at once, and your edits are more reliable when files are focused. Prefer smaller, focused files over large ones. When a file grows large, that is often a signal it is doing too much. This reinforces SOLID — it is both an architectural principle and a practical constraint of LLM context.

When in doubt, open the specific rule file listed above for the full text.

## Prompt Commands

> **Dev:** When `"devMode": true` is set in `aic.config.json` at the project root, substitute `pnpm aic` for `npx @jatbas/aic` in every command below (run from the repo root).

Use these rules for all five AIC prompt commands. Present data like a polished dashboard, not raw JSON.

**General formatting (all commands):**

- Use human-readable labels only — never show raw JSON keys as column headers or labels.
- Format large numbers with commas (e.g. 8,484,717).
- Percentages: exactly 1 decimal place and a % symbol (e.g. 78.2%).
- Timestamps: show as relative time (e.g. "2 min ago"); add ISO in parentheses only if helpful.
- Null or missing values: show as "—" (em dash), never "null".
- Keep the one-line summary at the top of each command as specified below.
- Output only the summary line, the table, and (for status, last, chat-summary) the metric footnote below. **Do not add commentary, notes, interpretation, or explanations after the output.**
- **Metric footnote** (append after the table for status, last, and chat-summary — one line per metric; **never** append to any other response): `Exclusion rate: % of total repo tokens not included in the compiled prompt.` then `Budget utilization: % of token budget filled.`

---

- **"show aic status"** — When the user says this (or similar), run Bash with `npx @jatbas/aic status` (or `pnpm aic status` when `"devMode": true` is set in `aic.config.json`) from the project directory (or the `<N>d` variant when the user asks for a rolling **N**-day window, with **N** an integer from 1 through 3660), then relay stdout. Start the reply with one short line: **Status = project-level AIC status.** When a window is used, the table includes a **Time range** row: **Last 1 day** if **N** is 1, otherwise **Last N days**. Then display a formatted table using these labels and formats:

  | JSON key                             | Label                  | Format                                                                 |
  | ------------------------------------ | ---------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------- |
  | compilationsTotal                    | Compilations (total)   | number                                                                 |
  | compilationsToday                    | Compilations (today)   | number                                                                 |
  | totalTokensRaw → totalTokensCompiled | Tokens: raw → compiled | e.g. 8,484,717 → 15,739                                                |
  | totalTokensSaved                     | Tokens excluded        | formatted with commas                                                  |
  | budgetMaxTokens                      | Budget limit           | formatted with commas                                                  |
  | budgetUtilizationPct                 | Budget utilization     | percentage, 1 decimal (e.g. 78.2%)                                     |
  | cacheHitRatePct                      | Cache hit rate         | percentage, 1 decimal                                                  |
  | avgReductionPct                      | Avg exclusion rate     | percentage, 1 decimal                                                  |
  | guardByType                          | Guard findings         | type: count pairs, or "None"                                           |
  | topTaskClasses                       | Top task classes       | taskClass (count), comma-separated                                     |
  | lastCompilation                      | Last compilation       | intent, files selected/total, tokens, relative time (e.g. "2 min ago") |
  | installationOk                       | Installation           | "OK" or "Issues detected"                                              |
  | updateAvailable                      | Update available       | version or "—"                                                         |

  When `installationOk` is false and `installationNotes` is a non-empty string, add a **Notes** row whose text is `installationNotes`. JSON still includes `installationNotes` and `projectEnabled` for programmatic use; omit **Project** from the formatted table.

- **"show aic chat summary"** — When the user says "show aic chat summary" or asks for this workspace's AIC compilation stats, run Bash with `npx @jatbas/aic chat-summary --project <absolute workspace root>` (or `pnpm aic chat-summary --project <absolute workspace root>` when `"devMode": true` is set in `aic.config.json`), then relay stdout. Start the reply with one short line: **Chat = this conversation's AIC compilations.** Then display a formatted table using these labels and formats:

  | JSON key                      | Label              | Format                                         |
  | ----------------------------- | ------------------ | ---------------------------------------------- |
  | projectRoot                   | Project path       | text                                           |
  | compilationsInConversation    | Compilations       | number                                         |
  | totalTokensRaw                | Tokens (raw)       | formatted with commas                          |
  | totalTokensCompiled           | Tokens (compiled)  | formatted with commas                          |
  | totalTokensSaved              | Tokens excluded    | formatted with commas                          |
  | cacheHitRatePct               | Cache hit rate     | percentage, 1 decimal                          |
  | avgReductionPct               | Avg exclusion rate | percentage, 1 decimal                          |
  | budgetUtilizationPct          | Budget utilization | percentage, 1 decimal                          |
  | lastCompilationInConversation | Last compilation   | intent text + relative time (e.g. "5 min ago") |
  | topTaskClasses                | Top task classes   | taskClass (count), comma-separated             |

- **"show aic last"** — When the user says this (or similar), run Bash with `npx @jatbas/aic last` (or `pnpm aic last` when `"devMode": true` is set in `aic.config.json`) from the project directory, then relay stdout. Start the reply with one short line: **Last = most recent compilation.** Then display using these labels and formats:

  | JSON key                   | Label              | Format                                                        |
  | -------------------------- | ------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------- |
  | intent                     | Intent             | text                                                          |
  | filesSelected / filesTotal | Files              | "N selected / M total"                                        |
  | tokensCompiled             | Tokens compiled    | formatted with commas                                         |
  | budgetUtilizationPct       | Budget utilization | percentage, 1 decimal                                         |
  | tokenReductionPct          | Exclusion rate     | percentage, 1 decimal                                         |
  | created_at                 | Compiled           | relative time (e.g. "3 min ago")                              |
  | editorId                   | Editor             | text                                                          |
  | guard status               | Guard              | "Passed" or "N findings (types)"                              |
  | compiledPrompt             | Compiled prompt    | "Available (N chars) — ask to see it", or omit if not present |

- **"show aic projects"** — When the user says this (or similar), run Bash with `npx @jatbas/aic projects` (or `pnpm aic projects` when `"devMode": true` is set in `aic.config.json`), then relay stdout. Start the reply with one short line: **Projects = known AIC projects.** Display a formatted table with columns: Project ID, Path, Last seen, Compilation count. Use same general formatting rules (human-readable labels, commas for numbers, relative time for last seen, — for null).

- **"run aic model test"** — When the user says this (or similar), call the `aic_model_test` MCP tool with `{ "projectRoot": "<absolute workspace root>" }`. The tool returns a `probeId`, three challenges, and instructions. Solve challenge 1 (arithmetic) and challenge 2 (string-reverse). Then call `aic_compile` with intent exactly equal to `"model-test-<answer1>-<answer2>"` (replace with your computed answers). Finally call `aic_model_test` again with `{ "projectRoot": "<absolute workspace root>", "probeId": "<probeId from step 1>", "answers": [<arithmetic answer>, "<reversed string>"] }`. Display the result as a table with columns: Test, Result (Pass/Fail), Notes. Start the reply with one short line: **Model test = agent capability probe.**

## Maintenance

- Whenever a **rule** in `.cursor/rules/` is changed or added, review this router: update the context table and/or critical reminders so the map stays accurate.
- **Hooks sync:** Critical reminders above are injected by `.cursor/hooks/AIC-session-init.cjs` at session start. When you edit the critical reminders list, the hook stays in sync automatically (it reads this file). No need to edit hook code unless you change the section heading or structure.
- **Cross-editor sync:** This file and `.claude/CLAUDE.md` are the two canonical rule files. They must stay in sync. Architectural invariants, security rules, dependency rules, commit rules, ESLint rules, and test rules are identical across both. Only editor-specific mechanics differ (hooks vs manual `aic_compile` calls, prompt command wording). Prompt commands use shell `npx @jatbas/aic …` diagnostics, not MCP tool calls. When changing any shared rule, update in one commit: (1) this file, (2) `.claude/CLAUDE.md`, (3) `CLAUDE_MD_TEMPLATE` in `integrations/claude/install.cjs`, and (4) `CLAUDE_MD_TEMPLATE` in `mcp/src/install-trigger-rule.ts` — same bytes; see `AIC-claude-md-managed-section.mdc` (no version banner inside the managed body).
